## Strategy (Task 8, Route B)

The test cases below are mirrored both here (Lean model side) and in
`src/tracker.rs::tests::test_quorum_recently_active_correspondence`
(Rust source side).  Both sides must produce the same `expected` Boolean on the
same `(voters, entries, perspectiveOf)` input.

- **Lean side**: `#guard` evaluates `quorumRecentlyActive voters entries perspectiveOf == expected`
  at lake-build time.  A compile error means the Lean model gives a different answer.
- **Rust side**: `assert_eq!` in the test function verifies the same expected values at
  `cargo test` time.

Together they demonstrate that the Lean `quorumRecentlyActive` model agrees with
the Rust `ProgressTracker::quorum_recently_active` on all 14 correspondence cases.

## Lean model recap

```lean
def isActive (entries : List (Nat × Progress)) (perspectiveOf : Nat) (n : Nat) : Bool :=
  entries.any (fun e => e.1 == n && (e.1 == perspectiveOf || e.2.recent_active))

def quorumRecentlyActive (voters : List Nat) (entries : List (Nat × Progress))
    (perspectiveOf : Nat) : Bool :=
  hasQuorum voters (isActive entries perspectiveOf)
```

## Correspondence notes

The Lean model captures the **return value** semantics of `quorum_recently_active`.
The Rust function also mutates `recent_active` flags (side-effects), but those do
not affect the current return value.  The Lean model deliberately abstracts them.

**perspectiveOf must be in `entries`** to be counted as active.  In practice the
leader always has a `Progress` entry in `self.progress`, so this is a minor
abstraction detail that the test cases handle explicitly.

